comments.body:
The usual approach for a cache is to abstract the problem to a (key, value) storage. That is even more true when we have distributed cache.

Say this is available from interface like:
```
LayerProvider {
 Layer get(key);
 void set(key, value);
}
```

We need to find a reliable way to create a key for every layer that we would like to add to/obtain from the cache. It seems to me that it would be relatively easy to come up with the key for the layer by simply hashing the base layer sha and the current command.

Using this approach will eliminate the need for iterating over layers belonging to images that could be expensive in the context of distributed cache. It also will eliminate the need to track predecessor images, which in the context of CI could be non-trivial.

Note that we can implement the LayerProvider interface on top of the container registry repo and any S3 object storage etc allowing for flexibility for the users. For the local cache it might require some adaptation, but would be as easy as creating a map between the key and the local layers to implement the same interface for it.

I have no clear idea about how 4. (the noop tagging) can be solved. Calculating a complete image key without obtaining involved layers seems significantly harder. Maybe if we extend the provider interface with

```
LayerProvider {
  LayerMeta getMeta(key);
 ...
}
```

We might be able to store enough detail to evaluate if the commands will produce the same layer - say hash for the files that are copied for a copy command for example.
